## Summary

- Fixes browser tab leakage on `/new` when tabs were tracked under a peer-scoped runtime-policy session key but cleanup only searched the canonical session key.
- For direct-DM sessions without an explicit `SessionKey`, browser tabs are tracked with keys like `agent:main:telegram:default:direct:12345`, while `/new` cleanup previously passed only `agent:main:main` plus the old session UUID.
- Adds `resolveRuntimePolicySessionKey(...)` to the cleanup key list when it differs from the canonical `sessionKey`.

## Linked context

No linked issue.

## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)

- Behavior or issue addressed: `/new` did not close browser tabs tracked under peer-scoped sandbox keys for direct-DM sessions that resolve to canonical `agent:main:main`.
- Real environment tested: local OpenClaw source checkout on Linux; HEAD `5f47a55385b5b3a0b84f21f7d70d2598fc9eea69`.
- Exact steps or command run after this patch:
  1. Unit regression:
     ```bash
     node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/auto-reply/reply/session.test.ts -t "includes runtime-policy"
     ```
  2. Temporary integration proof (not committed to repo): copy the script below to `src/auto-reply/reply/session-bugb-e2e.test.ts`, then run:
     ```bash
     node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/auto-reply/reply/session-bugb-e2e.test.ts
     ```
- Evidence after fix:

