- Observed result after fix:
  - Unit test: cleanup mock receives `[sessionId, agent:main:main, agent:main:telegram:default:direct:12345]` for direct-DM `/new`.
  - Integration test case 1: tracked tab count goes from 1 to 0 after `/new`.
  - Integration test case 2: cleanup with only canonical keys leaves count at 1; adding peer-scoped key clears it to 0.
- What was not tested: full gateway + live channel roundtrip; real Chrome MCP tab close against a running browser.
- Proof limitations or environment constraints: no live channel credentials in this proof run; integration proof uses real in-memory tab registry helpers with a no-op `closeTab`.
- Before evidence: pre-fix cleanup only passed `[sessionId, agent:main:main]`, missing peer-scoped key; integration baseline left tracked tab count at 1 until peer-scoped key was included.

## Tests and validation

- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/auto-reply/reply/session.test.ts -t "includes runtime-policy"` — pass
- Temporary `session-bugb-e2e.test.ts` integration proof — 2/2 pass at HEAD `5f47a55385b5b3a0b84f21f7d70d2598fc9eea69`
- Added committed regression test: `includes runtime-policy (peer-scoped) key in cleanup for direct-DM sessions`

## Risk checklist

Did user-visible behavior change? (`Yes`)

Did config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`No`)

Did security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`No`)

What is the highest-risk area?

Browser tab cleanup key expansion on session reset.

How is that risk mitigated?

Only adds an extra lookup key when `resolveRuntimePolicySessionKey` differs from `sessionKey`; no config/default surface changes; covered by unit test plus integration proof above.

